Quantum Engineering¶

In [ ]:
dev = qml.device("default.qubit", wires=4)
# Random circuit parameters
rand_params = np.random.uniform(high=2 * np.pi, size=(n_layers, 4))

@qml.qnode(dev) # Represents a quantum node in the hybrid computational graph
def circuit(phi):
    # Encoding of 4 classical input values
    for j in range(4):
        qml.RY(np.pi * phi[j], wires=j)

    # Random quantum circuit
    RandomLayers(rand_params, wires=list(range(4)))

    # Measurement producing 4 classical output values
    return [qml.expval(qml.PauliZ(j)) for j in range(4)]

Quanvolution - Image pre-processing method¶

In [ ]:
def quanv(image):
    """Convolves the input image with many applications of the same quantum circuit."""
    out = np.zeros((14, 14, 4))

    # Loop over the coordinates of the top-left pixel of 2X2 squares
    for j in range(0, 28, 2):
        for k in range(0, 28, 2):
            # Process a squared 2x2 region of the image with a quantum circuit
            q_results = circuit(
                [
                    image[j, k, 0],
                    image[j, k + 1, 0],
                    image[j + 1, k, 0],
                    image[j + 1, k + 1, 0]
                ]
            )
            # Assign expectation values to different channels of the output pixel (j/2, k/2)
            for c in range(4):
                out[j // 2, k // 2, c] = q_results[c]
    return out

Quantum Image Pre-Processing¶

In [ ]:
if PREPROCESS == True:
    q_train_images = []
    start_train = time.time()
    print("Quantum pre-processing of train images:")
    for idx, img in enumerate(train_images):
        print("{}/{}        ".format(idx + 1, n_train), end="\r")
        q_train_images.append(quanv(img))
    q_train_images = np.asarray(q_train_images)
    end_train = time.time()

    q_test_images = []
    start_test = time.time()
    print("\nQuantum pre-processing of test images:")
    for idx, img in enumerate(test_images):
        print("{}/{}        ".format(idx + 1, n_test), end="\r")
        q_test_images.append(quanv(img))
    q_test_images = np.asarray(q_test_images)
    end_test = time.time()

    q_val_images = []
    start_val = time.time()
    print("\nQuantum pre-processing of validation images:")
    for idx, img in enumerate(val_images):
        print("{}/{}        ".format(idx + 1, n_test), end="\r")
        q_val_images.append(quanv(img))
    q_val_images = np.asarray(q_val_images)
    end_val = time.time()

    # Save pre-processed images
    np.save(SAVE_PATH + "q_train_images.npy", q_train_images)
    np.save(SAVE_PATH + "q_test_images.npy", q_test_images)
    np.save(SAVE_PATH + "q_val_images.npy", q_val_images)

    # Calculate and print time taken for pre-processing
    print("Time taken for pre-processing train images: {} seconds".format(end_train - start_train))
    print("Time taken for pre-processing test images: {} seconds".format(end_test - start_test))
    print("Time taken for pre-processing val images: {} seconds".format(end_val - start_val))

Basic Quantum-Classical CNN¶

In [ ]:
def basic_model():
    """Initializes and returns a custom Keras model
    which is ready to be trained."""
    model = keras.models.Sequential([
        keras.layers.Flatten(),
        keras.layers.Dense(10, activation="softmax")
    ])

    model.compile(
        optimizer='adam',
        loss="sparse_categorical_crossentropy",
        metrics=["accuracy"],
    )
    return model

Quantum-Classical Hybrid Convolutional Neural Network - Xception Architecture¶

Custom Xception Model Development¶

In [ ]:
def nextGenModel(imageSizes, totalClasses):
    # Image input sizes
    inputs = keras.Input(shape=imageSizes)

    # Convolution
    """
    We add 128 filters which will scan over an image in order to condense/extract
    the relevant information inside that image to make an output classification

    Filter specs: 128 Filters and moves 2 block at a time with 3 kernal
    """
    iA = layers.Conv2D(128, 3, strides=2, padding="same")(inputs)

    # Normalization increases NN stability
    iA = layers.BatchNormalization()(iA)

    # Activation
    """
    We convert any negative values to 0 that allows us preserve positive value
    """
    iA = layers.Activation("relu")(iA)

    # ResNet blocks
    previousLayersActivationBlock = iA

    """
    loop through size of filters 256, 512, 728
    """
    for filterSize in [256, 512, 728]:
        iA = layers.Activation("relu")(iA)
        """
        SeparableConv2D - spatial convolution on each channel of given filter size
        """
        iA = layers.Conv2D(filterSize, 3, padding="same")(iA)
        iA = layers.BatchNormalization()(iA)

        iA = layers.Activation("relu")(iA)
        iA = layers.Conv2D(filterSize, 3, padding="same")(iA)
        iA = layers.BatchNormalization()(iA)

        """
        Goes through our images and condences them
        Returns back the value after relu activation, scans through the image value and condence the information
        """

        iA = layers.MaxPooling2D(3, strides=2, padding="same")(iA)
        # Projection shorcut
        """
        Matches the dimensions by 1 x 1 to learn linear projection of our ResNet activation block
        """
        residual = layers.Conv2D(filterSize, 1, strides=2, padding="same")(previousLayersActivationBlock)

        # shortcut connection with iA output
        iA = layers.add([iA, residual])

        # storing current state of activations for next block
        previousLayersActivationBlock = iA

    # Final Layers with 1024 filters
    iA = layers.Conv2D(1024, 3, padding="same")(iA)
    iA = layers.BatchNormalization()(iA)
    iA = layers.Activation("relu")(iA)

    # Each feature map average calculation (data dimensions reduction)
    iA = layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D()(iA)

    # Use single unit (sigmod) when classes are 2 otherwise units equal to classes (multiclass)
    if totalClasses == 2:
        units = 1
    else:
        units = totalClasses

    # Prevent overfitting by setting input units to 0 during each update while training
    iA = layers.Dropout(0.25)(iA)

    # Final classification
    outputs = layers.Dense(units, activation='softmax')(iA)

    # Creation
    model = keras.Model(inputs, outputs)

    # Compilation
    model.compile(
        optimizer="adam",
        loss="sparse_categorical_crossentropy",
        metrics=["accuracy"],
    )

    # Returns the created model
    return model

Universal model evaluator¶

In [ ]:
def evaluateModel(model, test_images, test_labels):
    # Evaluate the model
    loss, acc = model.evaluate(test_images, test_labels, verbose=0)
    print("Accuracy: {:5.2f}%".format(100 * acc))
    print("Loss: {:5.2f}".format(loss))

    # Predictions
    predictions = model.predict(test_images)
    predicted_labels = np.argmax(predictions, axis=1)

    # Confusion matrix
    confusion = tf.math.confusion_matrix(test_labels, predicted_labels, num_classes=10)
    print("Confusion matrix:")
    print(confusion.numpy())

    # Plot the confusion matrix
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    plt.imshow(confusion, cmap=plt.cm.Blues)
    plt.xlabel("Predicted labels")
    plt.ylabel("True labels")
    plt.xticks(list(range(10)))
    plt.yticks(list(range(10)))
    plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
    plt.colorbar()
    plt.title("Confusion Matrix")
    plt.show()

    # Plot some test images with predictions
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 3, figsize=(9, 9))
    for i, ax in enumerate(axes.flat):
        ax.imshow(test_images[i, :, :, 0], cmap="gray")
        ax.axis("off")
        ax.set_title("Predicted: {}".format(predicted_labels[i]))
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    # Classification report
    from sklearn.metrics import classification_report
    print("Classification Report:")
    print(classification_report(test_labels, predicted_labels))

    # ROC curve and AUC
    from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc
    from sklearn.preprocessing import label_binarize

    # Convert labels to one-hot encoded format
    y_true = label_binarize(test_labels, classes=list(range(10)))
    y_pred = predictions

    # Compute ROC curve and ROC area for each class
    fpr = dict()
    tpr = dict()
    roc_auc = dict()
    for i in range(10):
        fpr[i], tpr[i], _ = roc_curve(y_true[:, i], y_pred[:, i])
        roc_auc[i] = auc(fpr[i], tpr[i])

    # Compute micro-average ROC curve and ROC area
    fpr["micro"], tpr["micro"], _ = roc_curve(y_true.ravel(), y_pred.ravel())
    roc_auc["micro"] = auc(fpr["micro"], tpr["micro"])

    # Plot ROC curve
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    plt.plot(fpr["micro"], tpr["micro"], label='Micro-average ROC curve (area = {:0.2f})'.format(roc_auc["micro"]), color='deeppink', linestyle=':')
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', linestyle='--')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.show()

    return predicted_labels
